          "body": "Of the four kings, Zedekiah receives the Chronicler's most detailed theological indictment (36:12-13). Three verbs describe his rebellion: he did not 'humble himself' before Jeremiah (36:12); he 'stiffened his neck' (36:13); he 'hardened his heart against turning to the LORD' (36:13). These are not casual moral failings — they are the classic Old Testament vocabulary of covenant stubbornness. 'Stiffened his neck' is the same phrase used of the Exodus generation (Exodus 32:9; Deuteronomy 9:6, 13); 'hardened his heart' echoes Pharaoh's paradigmatic resistance (Exodus 7:3). By using this language, the Chronicler is telling the reader that Zedekiah has recapitulated the most catastrophic hardness in Israel's memory. And the failure has a specific, nameable form: refusal of prophetic correction. He 'did not humble himself before Jeremiah the prophet who spoke for the LORD' (36:12). Humility before God's prophet is humility before God; refusal of the prophet is refusal of the LORD Himself. The Chronicler's entire theology of royal success and failure hinges on this: kings who humble themselves survive; kings who do not, fall."
