          "title": "Compassion, contempt, and the point of no return",
          "body": "Verses 15-16 are the theological heart of the chapter and arguably of the entire book. The Chronicler pauses the narrative of royal failure to offer an explanation from God's perspective. The explanation has two movements: divine initiative and human response. The LORD's initiative: He 'sent word to them again and again by His messengers, because He had compassion on His people and on His dwelling place' (36:15). The Hebrew for 'again and again' (hashkem v'shaloach) literally means 'rising early to send' — rising before dawn to dispatch messengers, a Hebrew idiom for urgent and persistent effort. The motive is named explicitly: compassion. God did not withdraw in cold silence; He pressed His warnings upon them. The human response: they 'continually mocked the messengers of God, despised His words and scoffed at His prophets' (36:16). Three verbs of contempt, each slightly stronger than the last — mock, despise, scoff. And they did it 'continually' — not in a moment of weakness but as a sustained posture. The result: 'the wrath of the LORD arose against His people, until there was no remedy' (36:16). 'No remedy' (ein marpe) — literally 'no healing.' The wound has been allowed to fester past the point where medicine can help. This is among the most solemn statements in the Old Testament: God's wrath aroused not by sudden offense but by persistent, sustained contempt of His persistent, sustained mercy."
