          "body": "The chapter's final two verses (36:22-23) perform a pivot that is among the most dramatic in the entire Old Testament. Everything has been heading toward catastrophe — kings deposed, temples plundered, walls burned, survivors exiled. Then: 'Now in the first year of Cyrus king of Persia — in order to fulfill the word of the LORD by the mouth of Jeremiah — the LORD stirred up the spirit of Cyrus king of Persia' (36:22). The Chronicler does three things in this sentence. First, he dates the restoration precisely — 'the first year of Cyrus' (539 BC). Second, he frames it theologically — 'in order to fulfill the word of the LORD.' Third, he names the divine agency — 'the LORD stirred up the spirit of Cyrus.' Isaiah 44:28-45:1 had named Cyrus by name more than a century before his birth as the LORD's 'shepherd' and 'anointed' who would command the rebuilding of Jerusalem. The Chronicler now confirms that Isaiah was right. Cyrus's proclamation — 'the LORD, the God of heaven, has given me all the kingdoms of the earth, and He has appointed me to build Him a house in Jerusalem' (36:23) — is a pagan emperor's acknowledgment of Israelite covenant theology. The chapter that opened with four failing Davidic kings closes with a Persian king doing what none of them could: redirecting the course of history back toward Jerusalem and the house of God."
