        "excerpt": "Then they burned the house of God and broke down the wall of Jerusalem, and burned all its fortified buildings with fire and destroyed all its valuable articles.",
        "body": "Having explained the theological cause of the fall (36:14-17), the Chronicler narrates its consequences with unsparing brevity. Three categories of loss are inventoried: the articles of the house of God (36:18), the physical structures (36:19), and the people (36:20). The sequence is significant — sacred objects first, then stone and mortar, then human beings. The Chronicler's order suggests the hierarchy of what mattered: the covenant symbols of God's presence, then the city that housed them, then the people who were supposed to maintain them.\n\nThe temple articles had already begun leaving in earlier deportations — Jehoiakim's reign (36:7) and Jehoiachin's reign (36:10) each saw portions taken. Now in verse 18 the remainder go to Babylon: 'All the articles of the house of God, great and small, and the treasures of the house of the LORD, and the treasures of the king and of his officers.' The 'great and small' is exhaustive — nothing is left. The Chronicler's readers knew that these very articles would be returned under Ezra (Ezra 1:7-11); naming their complete removal sets up the restoration.\n\nVerse 19 narrates the destruction of Jerusalem's physical fabric in four clauses: burned the house of God, broke down the wall, burned all fortified buildings, destroyed all valuable articles. For the Chronicler's audience, this destruction was recent memory — their parents or grandparents had seen it. The temple, the wall, the fortified buildings — these were the physical expressions of covenant identity. Their destruction did not mean God was absent; it meant the covenant had reached its judgment clause (2 Chronicles 7:20: 'I will uproot you from My land which I have given you').\n\nVerse 20 closes the fall narrative with the fate of the survivors: 'Those who had escaped from the sword he carried away to Babylon; and they were servants to him and to his sons until the rule of the kingdom of Persia.' The phrase 'until the rule of the kingdom of Persia' is the Chronicler's first hint of a horizon — exile has a terminus. Babylon's sovereignty is temporary. The passive construction 'were servants' names the humiliation without dwelling on it; the 'until' clause lifts the reader's eyes toward what follows."
